	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p>As you are chief magistrate of this city&#44; and as such entrusted with the safety of all<lb/> the inhabitants&#44; I trust that I do not presume too much by intruding on your time<lb/> which must be now fully occupied.</p>
				<p>You some weeks ago made a proclamation against mass violence&#44; and it then had<lb/> occurred to me that I about have to complain of any threatened application toward<lb/> myself of this worse than Prussian tyranny.  But the fact is so nevertheless.  Yesterday<lb/> a certain lawyer <persName>M A Dropsie Esq.</persName>&#44; whose name you perhaps know&#44; said to me in the<lb/> course of some conversation referring to the important conflict now progressing&#58; &#8220;You better take<lb/> care what you say&#59; you are already on the <hi rend="underline">suspected</hi> list&#44; and you may be compelled<lb/> to quit the city before long&#33;&#8221;  Now I know nothing of a <hi rend="underline">legal</hi> or illegal suspected<lb/> list of the inhabitants of this city&#44; nor am I conscious of any offense against the laws of this<lb/> corporation&#44; or the constitution&#44; or the laws of the State of the Union&#44; why I should be suspected</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>of anything&#44; much less why I should be ordered by anyone to quit <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.<lb/>  You will therefore greatly oblige an old resident&#44; who knew your grandfather<lb/> thirty years ago&#44; whether such a suspected list is in existence&#44; and if so&#44;<lb/> for what cause my name was placed thereon&#59; and if so whether I shall be<lb/> liable to a summary expulsion from this place&#59; and that i may make on time<lb/> the necessary preparation&#44; to go back to a country less free than this&#44;<lb/> but where the people at least have the assurance&#44; that they are not liable to be<lb/> molested by anyone&#44; who in time of trouble may endeavor far more malice<add>&#63;</add><lb/> to denounce them to an irresponsible power which being unknown to the law&#44;<lb/> places the law &#38; common sense at defiance.</p>
				<p>It is useless to enlarge more on this matter&#44; as the within is sufficient.<lb/>  I make no formal complaint against <persName>Mr Dropsie</persName>&#44; as I trust in the frank<lb/> assurance of the <persName>Mayor</persName> of <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> that he knows nothing of any charge against<lb/> me.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Re<hi rend="sup">y</hi></p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">IL</persName></p>
				<p><placeName>1227 W.</placeName> <date>June 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> 1861</date></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Office of the Mayor</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>OF THE</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>CITY OF PHILADELPHIA</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>June 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> 1861</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>No 1227 Walnut St.</placeName></p>
				<p>Sir&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The contents of<lb/> your note of this morning<lb/> greatly astonish me.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I do not know why the<lb/> language of which you<lb/> complain should have been used by <persName>Mr. M. A. Dropsie.</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I can with pleasure<lb/> assure you that your loyalty<lb/> has never been impinged&#44;<lb/> so far as I am aware&#8212;and<lb/> I have no knowledge of the<lb/> existence of a &#8220;suspected list&#8221;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am very Respectfully</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName role="author">Alexander Henry</persName></p>
		</body>
